messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Here is the analysis for the signup endpoint implemented in UserAccountController.

- Full HTTP request path: /api/account/signup
  - This is derived from the class-level @RequestMapping("/api/account") plus the method-level @PostMapping("/signup").

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable? No
  - The controller defines specific mappings:
    - GET /api/account/{account_id}
    - POST /api/account/signup
  - The signup endpoint only supports POST, so not all methods are acceptable.

- HEAD method acceptable? No
  - The signup endpoint does not define a HEAD mapping. In Spring, HEAD is not implicitly enabled for non-GET mappings. Since signup is POST, HEAD is not supported by the code for this endpoint.

- POST method acceptable? Yes
  - The signup endpoint is explicitly annotated with @PostMapping("/signup"), so POST is supported.

- OPTIONS method acceptable? No
  - There is no explicit OPTIONS mapping for this endpoint. Without an explicit handler or a global configuration, OPTIONS is not considered acceptable based on the code.

- TRACE method acceptable? No
  - There is no explicit TRACE mapping for this endpoint, so not acceptable by the code.

- GET method acceptable? No
  - The signup endpoint itself is not a GET mapping; only POST is defined for /api/account/signup. GET is not applicable to this endpoint.

- PUT method acceptable? No
  - Not defined for this endpoint.

- DELETE method acceptable? No
  - Not defined for this endpoint.

- PATCH method acceptable? No
  - Not defined for this endpoint.

Explanation:
- The controller is annotated with @RequestMapping("/api/account"), giving the base path /api/account.
- The signup endpoint is defined as @PostMapping("/signup"), resulting in the full path /api/account/signup and accepting only the POST method.
- Other HTTP methods are not mapped to this endpoint, so they are not acceptable according to the code. HEAD is not automatically inferred for POST mappings in Spring; unless explicitly mapped, it is not considered acceptable here.
